The Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) has urged capital market operators to continue to make full disclosures on the impact of COVID-19 on their businesses The advice was given in a circular issued by the commission to the operators. The SEC stated: “While we continue to monitor the evolvement of the pandemic and its impact on the capital market, all regulated entities are reminded to make adequate disclosures and report on how the pandemic is impacting operations and discharge of services to investors and other stakeholders. “We also wish to assure investors that while efforts are on-going to ensure that capital market services remain accessible, the Commission’s priority is the protection of investors. Dear valued readers, subscribe to the Daily Trust e-paper to continue enjoying our diet of authoritative news. Kindly subscribe here The market regulator also stated that following government’s partial easing of the lockdown measures introduced to minimize the spread of Covid-19 nationwide, it had re-opened its head office for operations. The commission stated further that due to the need to protect its stakeholders and members of staff, stakeholders should use its various e-channels to communicate and interact with the commission and that physical visits should only be considered as a last resort. Other guidelines issued by the SEC are that all meetings and events will be convened electronically until further notice; all filings shall continue to be received electronically; all visitors will be subjected to temperature checks and hand sanitization before gaining access to the commission’s building; and also visitors are expected to wear facemasks and abide by social distancing rules while present in the commission’s facility. SEC insists disclosures must go on despite Covid-19 SEC asks Nigerians to explore capital market investment options SEC introduces e-filing, processing of applications/returns